# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: perth-stadium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] The **1897 VFL season** was the inaugural season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] The season ran from 8 May to 4 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a three-week finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] Eight Victorian Football Association (VFA) clubs – Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne, South Melbourne and St Kilda – featured in the inaugural season after seceding from the VFA in 1896.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] Essendon won the inaugural premiership after winning all three of its finals matches, with Geelong finishing as runners-up with two wins.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] Geelong won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James and Melbourne's Jack Leith tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] In 1897, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] Each team played each other twice in a home-and-away season of 14 rounds.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] Once the 14-round home-and-away season had finished, the 1897 VFL Premiers were determined according to the conditions dictated by the specific format and conventions of the 1897 Finals System, which was used in this season only.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] The following table can be sorted from biggest winning margin to biggest losing margin for each round.
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] If two or more matches in a round are decided by the same margin, these margins are sorted by percentage (i.e. the lowest-scoring winning team is ranked highest and the lowest-scoring losing team is ranked lowest).
[src:perth-stadium/1897-vfl-season] Opponents are listed above the margins and home matches are in bold.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The **1898 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Essendon Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held in Melbourne on 24 September 1898.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match was played to determine the premiers for the 1898 VFL season.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The game was played under atrocious ground conditions in front of 16,538 people at the Junction Oval.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match is recognised as the first VFL grand final, although the term "grand final" was not in wide use until 1931.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] It was the first time that Victorian Football League premiership was decided in a final match, as the 1897 premiership was won under a different finals system by Essendon when they finished above three other clubs on the finals series ladder.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both Fitzroy back pocket Stan Reid and the Essendon full-forward Charlie Moore later died in South Africa in active service during the Anglo-Boer War—Moore on 5 May 1901, and Reid on 23 June 1901.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] During the 1898 home-and-away season, all teams played each other twice.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The winners of the two sections were Fitzroy and Collingwood, respectively (for results of all of the round-robin matches); and, a week later (17 September 1898), the two teams played each other at Brunswick Street Oval, with Fitzroy winning the match 2.10 (22) to 1.5 (11).
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] After the VFL referred the decision to the VFL's Match Arrangement Committee, they, upon the express instructions of that committee, rejected the suggestions of the two teams outright and the match was controversially scheduled to be played at the Junction Oval.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The Junction Oval was in an appalling condition, as the ground had not been used since the second Saturday of the sectional round-robin match three weeks earlier (3 September); and, since then, it had been thoroughly top-dressed and "cultivated" in anticipation of the coming cricket season.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Also, the cricket ground's asphalt cycling track that lay between the boundary line and the fence presented a considerable danger to the footballers.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Despite being the "challenger", Essendon flatly refused to play in the scheduled match, declaring that it would rather forfeit the match and the premiership than play on such a dangerous surface.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] This view was also strongly supported by Fitzroy, whose captain, Alec Sloan, had also taken the step of signing a statutory declaration to the effect that, in his opinion, the ground was entirely unfit to play on.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The VFL, perhaps somewhat driven by the fact that the attraction of a finals system was one of the major reasons that the eight teams had left the VFA and formed the VFL in the first place, had a special meeting to hear Essendon's appeal.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] While it chose to endorse the committee's decision, it also did everything it could to convince Essendon to play the match.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon did not actually agree to play the match until the night before the game; ultimately, this "in-doubt-until-the-last-minute match" was still attended by 16,538 paying spectators; it certainly would have been a much larger crowd otherwise.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] The ground had been in such a dreadful condition that, in the week prior to the match, over 40 dray-loads of rubbish, soil and street-sweepings had been taken from the ground.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] All of this last-minute work greatly improved the playing surface at the ground, with sportswriters noting that while the ground was imperfect, it was nevertheless fit for use.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Dry, windy weather and patches of ground where the topsoil had not bound meant that players often fell on the grassless slippery ground for want of some sort of grip, and play was often impeded by clouds of dust.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] To prevent any repeat of the events leading up to the 1898 challenge final, the VFL agreed that from 1899 they would schedule for a possible challenge final in advance.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] In 1898, all VFL teams had 20 on-the-field players and no "reserves".
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Although there were no reserves, any player who had left the playing field for any reason at all could resume his place on the field at any time.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy selected a set of brothers in its team: Jim and Mick Grace (see TALK page).
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon had beaten Fitzroy in their round 1 and round 8 matches by 53 and 43 points, respectively.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had beaten Essendon by 29 points in the third match of their round-robin Sectional matches.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both teams had great difficulty playing football in the appalling ground conditions—as evidenced by the low scores—and the tough, bustling Fitzroy team handled the conditions far better than the Essendon team that had hoped to spread the game out as far as possible.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy took the lead in the first few minutes of the match, and Essendon were never able to catch up.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon were further demoralized when Fitzroy champion forward and follower Mick Grace, renowned for his marking skill and kicking prowess, flew high over a pack to take a spectacular high mark and kicked a long-range goal.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] In a very tight, defensive second half, as the playing conditions deteriorated even further, only one goal was scored.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy went on to beat Essendon 5.8 (38) to 3.5 (23).
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] The **1898 VFL season** was the second season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 14 May to 24 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating Essendon by 15 points in the 1898 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's first VFL premiership.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] Essendon won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] Collingwood's Archie Smith won the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] In 1898, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1898 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] The VFL introduced a new system of finals for the 1898 season.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] The new system, which was used from 1898–1900, allowed all clubs to compete for the major premiership, with the minor premiers having the right to challenge for the premiership.
[src:perth-stadium/1898-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Essendon won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] It was the second annual grand final of the Victorian Football League.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 4,823 spectators, was won by Fitzroy by a margin of 1 point, becoming the first club to claim back-to-back VFL premierships.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had won the minor premiership in the 1899 season, while South Melbourne had finished sixth after the home-and-away season.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] In the sectional major rounds, Fitzroy and South Melbourne each finished with records of 3–0 to qualify for the final.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Under the finals system in place, this match was the final of the major round, played between the two section winners.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Had South Melbourne won the match, it would not have immediately won the season's premiership; Fitzroy, as the minor premiers, would have had the right to challenge South to a rematch for the premiership on the following Saturday.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Meanwhile, Fitzroy could clinch the premiership win a win in this match.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] "The last match of the season for the league premiership was played on Saturday, when Fitzroy and South Melbourne met on the St.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Unfortunately, steady rain, which had fallen all the morning, continued nearly all the afternoon, making the conditions under which the game was played unsatisfactory for the players and most unpleasant for spectators.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] The "weather committee" had not met to consider the advisability of a postponement, and when the teams assembled South Melbourne suggested deferring the match until next Saturday, but Fitzroy preferred to brave the elements.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] The assembling of about 4000 spectators in the unfavorable circumstances indicated clearly that, if the weather had kept fine, the attendance would have been enormous.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] As it was, those present evinced keen interest in the game, every notable bit of good play being heartily cheered.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Amongst the onlookers were a number of enthusiasts from Geelong, who came up by special train.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] had the ground in splendid order until the rain came, and even after the steady downpour, extending over many hours, it played very, much better than could have been expected, reflecting great credit on the experienced and skilful curator. ...
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] The strong wind from the southern end of the ground favoured South Melbourne in the opening quarter.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Harry Lampe kicked the first two goals of the match, and Fitzroy's only score, a behind, came when a kick from Mick Grace hit the post.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy then had the advantage of the wind in the second quarter.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Goals to Mick Grace and Fred Fontaine had them ahead at half time.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Charlie Colgan gave South Melbourne the lead with the only goal of the third term.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Bill McSpeerin's goal 15 minutes into the final quarter gave Fitzroy the win.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy's Bert Sharpe, the team's centre half-forward in its 1898 premiership side, was a late withdrawal from the side due to the death of his father the day before the Grand Final; his teammates wore black armbands for that match.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-season] The **1899 VFL season** was the third season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 13 May to 16 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating South Melbourne by one point in the 1899 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's second (consecutive and overall) VFL premiership.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy also won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James won his second leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-season] In 1899, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:perth-stadium/1899-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1899 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium was built by a consortium led by Multiplex.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The announcement of the Burswood location in June 2011 followed a series of earlier proposals for the stadium, including locations in Subiaco and East Perth.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It was completed during late 2017 and officially opened on 21 January 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium's total capacity is 61,266, including standing room, extendable to 65,000 seats for rectangular sports.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It is the third-largest stadium in Australia (after the Melbourne Cricket Ground and Stadium Australia).
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In 2003, the Government of Western Australia led by Alan Carpenter approved Terms of Reference for a review to examine the future of major sporting venues in Western Australia with Terms of Reference approved in December 2003.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Having spent 2004 working with Football and Cricket bodies to try and advance the project the Government decided, in 2005, to appoint a taskforce.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The taskforce released its final report in May 2007.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The report recommended the construction of a new 60,000-seat stadium at either Kitchener Park (which adjoins Subiaco Oval) or in East Perth, which would be suitable for Australian rules football, cricket and also rectangular-field sports such as soccer, rugby union and rugby league.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The taskforce recommended against the further development of Subiaco Oval, which would be demolished.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In July 2007, the Government of Western Australia announced its preference to build a new 60,000-seat stadium rather than re-develop Subiaco Oval, and in early 2008 it confirmed that Subiaco Oval would be demolished for the new Perth super-stadium to be built next door at Kitchener Park.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] This site was chosen ahead of the other suggested site at the old East Perth Power Station, which was set aside to house a new $500 million museum.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The new stadium at Subiaco was scheduled to be built between 2011 and 2016, with the majority of the stadium to be completed in 2014.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Subiaco Oval was to be demolished between 2014 and 2016 to allow the end of construction on Perth Stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The staged construction would have allowed for Australian rules football to be played at the new venue by 2014, when the stadium was two-thirds completed with an initial capacity of 40,000 seats.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The final stage would be completed in 2016 and expand the stadium's capacity to 60,000.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Stadium plans suggested its playing surface would have been oval in shape to accommodate Australian rules football and cricket games.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium was also expected to have retractable seating which would have reconfigured the venue to make it suitable for rectangular-field sports codes, such as soccer, rugby union and rugby league.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] These retractable seats were to number 22,000, and were to be situated along the touch lines and behind the posts in the rectangular configuration.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] With an overall planned capacity of 60,000, Perth Stadium would have been Western Australia's largest sports venue, and it was designed to be built such that the capacity could be increased to 70,000 if needed in the future.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium was expected to be primarily used for Australian rules football with the ability to host cricket, rugby union, rugby league and soccer matches.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It was planned that it would be the home ground for the West Coast Eagles and Fremantle Dockers, the two Western Australian teams in the Australian Football League.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It was also planned to host rugby union Test matches, soccer and rock concerts.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In reality AFL matches have been joined by the AFLW games and WAFL grand finals.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The cost for the Kitchener Park stadium was expected to reach $1.1 billion, including $800 million on construction of the stadium itself and $300 million on associated infrastructure, property acquisition, escalation, transport infrastructure and other costs.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Construction of the new stadium would have involved moving 27 private residences and moving residents from another 66 state housing properties surrounding Subiaco Oval.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] These state housing tenants would have been relocated within the Subiaco area.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The project was going to be funded by the Government of Western Australia.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Following the election of a new State Government under Colin Barnett, the new stadium's plans were scrapped in early February 2009.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Barnett stated that a new stadium would not be considered for at least two years.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] As a result of Australia's failed bid for the 2022 World Cup, $250 million in potential federal government funding for a new stadium was also withdrawn in December 2010.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In June 2011, the State Government announced that the new stadium would be built in Burswood on the northern section of the Burswood Park golf course.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The government stated that the Burswood site was preferred because it was unconstrained by surrounding developments and had the additional benefit of being government-owned.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It would also allow for a special events six-platform Perth Stadium railway station to be built and could be connected to the central business district via a pedestrian bridge across the Swan River to East Perth.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] A car park was not built to service the stadium, with visitors expected to either park in the city and walk across the bridge or use public transport.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Government stated that planning for the new stadium at Burswood was due to be completed by mid-2012, with construction commencing in 2014 and scheduled for completion in 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It announced Multiplex as the contract holders for the construction of the stadium and appointed the firm Populous as the project's architectural consultants.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Following the Barnett Government's announcement to move the site of the proposed stadium to Burswood, it stated that the stadium would cost around $700 million, with an extra $300 million allocated to public transport works.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] However, in December 2011 Premier Colin Barnett stated that it was too early to say what the final cost would be, explaining that "No one can put a price on it until it's designed, until it goes out to tender".
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The previous Government's Major Stadia Taskforce had earlier put the total cost of the Burswood stadium option, including transport needs, at $1.147 billion.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Australian Football League agreed to help pay for Perth's new stadium at Burswood, although it was not revealed how much money it would contribute.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] However, the nearby Crown Perth, which is expected to benefit commercially from the presence of the stadium, was not asked by the Barnett Government to help meet the construction costs.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In October 2017 it was reported that the final cost of the completed stadium was $1.6 billion.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] This equated to an average cost per Western Australian household of $1500, and per person of $600.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In February 2018 a State Government inquiry into Western Australia's finances under the former Barnett government found that the full cost of the stadium including transport infrastructure will be $1.8 billion, around $200 million more than previous estimates.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The site is located on the Burswood Peninsula, previously known as the Swan Portland Cement Site.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Swan Portland Cement Company Ltd operated at the site from 1927 and James Hardie Industries operated at the adjacent site from the 1920s up until 1981.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The EPA report states that while undisturbed in the soil, the contamination poses no threat to public health but disturbing the site will result in airborne asbestos fibres and contamination from the soil.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The EPA recommended a management plan for any disturbance of asbestos contamination to be conducted by the Town of Victoria Park.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In November 2012, Victoria Park residents contacted the Health Department to notify them asbestos and other material had been unearthed by work on the southern parking lot of the Casino complex.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Alarmed residents feared asbestos exposure to locals, park users and Casino patrons.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Although the Health Department advised that no risk had been identified, stock piles were sprayed with hydromulch, windbreaks were put on fencing, contaminant levels were being monitored and paths and loose soil were sealed.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Premier's office advised that the Department of Building Management and Works were undertaking the project.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Health Department assured residents there was "no risk to the general public".
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The construction of the stadium affected Aboriginal communities.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Although the State Solicitor's Office advises that native title has been extinguished over the site, it has heritage significance for the local indigenous people, the Whadjuk Noongar, being a burial site.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Despite the Department of Indigenous Affairs advising the existence of the registered Aboriginal Heritage site affecting the Burswood Peninsula and East Perth foreshore, the site was deregistered by the Barnett Liberal State Government.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Previously the site was recognised by the Department of Aboriginal Affairs under the Aboriginal Heritage Act 1972 (AHA) as DAA site 15914: Burswood Island Burial.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] "Several culturally significant sites around WA have had their protection withdrawn in the past year on the basis they no longer fit the definition of a sacred site.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The first event to be held at the stadium was a Twenty20 cricket match between the Perth Scorchers and the England Lions on 11 December 2017, followed by a second match between the same teams two days later.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It was officially opened to the public on 21 January 2018 with a free open day for the community.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] During construction, then-Premier Colin Barnett had maintained that the government would not be selling the naming rights for the stadium as it would "not be appropriate for such a significant piece of State-owned infrastructure".
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Instead he suggested a name such as "Swan Stadium" or "River Stadium" – named after the adjacent Swan River – would be more appropriate.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Ultimately, the name Perth Stadium was settled on as it was more representative of Western Australia.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In the lead up to the state election in March 2017, Labor, then in opposition, announced that it would sell the naming rights for both Perth Stadium and Perth Arena as part of a plan to return the state budget to surplus if it were to win government.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Despite initially suggesting it might retain the Perth Stadium name or at least retain "Perth" in any naming rights arrangement, the new McGowan government announced on 8 November 2017 that the stadium would be officially known as Optus Stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Optus, the second-largest telecommunications company in Australia, and the state government agreed to a 10-year naming rights deal that is thought to be worth approximately $50 million in value.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] For international cricket matches, the stadium is known as Perth Stadium, due to Cricket Australia’s contractual obligations.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] As with the earlier plans for the new stadium at Kitchener Park, the stadium seats over 60,000 spectators, with the ability to seat up to 70,000 in rectangular mode.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Initially in the early design stages, it was hoped the venue could have the potential to expand to 80,000 seats in the future by adding a third tier along one wing and another tier on the opposite side of the ground each holding 10,000 seats.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Even at 61,266, Perth Stadium still has the third-biggest capacity of any stadium in the country, behind the Melbourne Cricket Ground and Accor Stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium's roof comprises a lightweight membrane textile that covers 85% of the seats.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It is supported by cantilevered trusses to give a halo effect, with all columns located behind the seating area.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The field is 165 m (541 ft) long and 130 m (430 ft) wide, 5 m (16 ft) longer than both the Melbourne Cricket Ground and Docklands Stadium in Melbourne, but 10 m (33 ft) shorter than Subiaco Oval which was 175 by 122 m (574 by 400 ft).
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] It is a multi-purpose facility able to hold not only sporting events such as Australian rules football and major rugby league, rugby union, cricket and soccer games, but major cultural events such as concerts and other entertainment events.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] During the Test Cricket match in December 2019, a temporary swimming pool was installed, similar to the one at The Gabba.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium is equipped with a range of state-of-the-art technological features designed to enhance the fan experience.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium leverages integrated technology for a seamless fan experience, including digital ticketing, sensor-equipped turnstiles, and a stadium app offering real-time information.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] There are two 340 m2 (3,700 sq ft) screens on either end of the stadium and over 1,000 TV screens located within the stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium provides robust connectivity through a multi-layer network built on Cisco's industrial-grade Wi-Fi 6 access points.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Additionally, Telstra enhances the coverage by blanketing the stadium in 5G signal.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium is serviced by over 50 food and beverage outlets, with patrons able to follow on-field action on TV screens.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Fans will never be more than 40 metres (130 ft) away from a bar or food outlet, with 75 percent of food supplied from locally owned and operated businesses.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Camfield, a large pub, microbrewery and function centre, is located outside the stadium and open seven days a week.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium has 748 male, 781 female and 60 accessible toilets.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Security features include an on-site police station, 650 CCTV cameras around the stadium and surrounding precinct, and freestanding metal detectors at the stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In February 2021 a rooftop tour branded "Halo" was opened at the stadium, allowing participants to walk around the stadium's roof.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In August 2021 a new viewing platform began construction on top of the roof on the western side of the stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The wheelchair accessible platform, which resembles a pull tab from above, projects 5 metres (16 ft) beyond both sides of the stadium roof and also features a section where visitors can lean over the playing field below while wearing a safety harness.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The platform and the attraction - branded "Vertigo" - both opened in March 2022.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] As the stadium is located on a peninsula with limited road access, the majority of visitors have to travel to and from the stadium primarily by public transport.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Public Transport Authority aims to have 83 percent of visitors use public transport.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The six-platform Perth Stadium railway station and 22-stand Perth Stadium Bus Station located nearby are expected to serve an estimated 28,000 and 8,000 passengers respectively on event days.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] For events, 8,600 people typically walk and cycle across the Swan River via the Windan Bridge, and an additional 14,300 walk across the Matagarup Bridge which connects the stadium precinct with public transport and car parks in East Perth.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] There are 600 bicycle parking spots located around the stadium precinct.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium has 1,400 car parking bays, but they are reserved for staff, premium ticket holders and disability parking.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] A 96-metre (315 ft) jetty was built near Matagarup Bridge and officially opened on 11 June 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Burswood Jetty allows all public and commercial vessels to drop off or pick up patrons with a 15-minute time limit.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Little Ferry Co. operates a service which operates Wednesday to Sunday to the jetty, while Captain Cook Cruises operates cruise transfers to and from the jetty on event days.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium is used for Australian rules football matches in the Australian Football League (AFL) from March–September.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium was constructed to provide a new home ground for the West Coast Eagles and Fremantle Dockers, Perth's two professional AFL clubs.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Fremantle's women's team hosted the first Australian rules football match at the venue against Collingwood on 10 February 2018, and the attendance of 41,975 was the highest stand-alone figure in domestic women's sport.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The first AFL premiership match to be played at the new stadium was contested between West Coast and Sydney on 25 March 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium became the twelfth venue to host a Grand Final in VFL/AFL history, when, due to the COVID-19 lockdown in Victoria precluding travel from the state, it hosted the 2021 AFL Grand Final.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The match saw the Melbourne Demons defeat the Western Bulldogs by 74 points to win their first AFL premiership since 1964.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] A total of 61,118 people attended, which at the time was the second highest crowd for the stadium and the biggest for an AFL game at the venue.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] An AFL State of Origin game played at the stadium on 14 February 2026 between Western Australia and Victoria, the first State of Origin since 2020 and the first match up between the two states since 1992, drew 58,141 spectators.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Cricket matches, such as One Day Internationals (ODI) and Twenty20s, are held at the stadium in the months of October–February.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Since late 2017, the Australia national cricket team play most of their Perth-based Tests, One Day and Twenty20 matches at the venue.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium is also the home ground of Big Bash League side Perth Scorchers, who relocated from the WACA Ground in 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The first major event at the stadium was an ODI match between Australia and England on 28 January 2018, which England won by 12 runs.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium became the 19th venue in Australia to host a One Day International cricket game.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Western Australian Cricket Association later confirmed that the stadium would host its first ever Test match, which began between Australia and India on 14 December 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium became the fourth venue in Australia to host a men's Day/night cricket Test match, when Australia took on New Zealand between 12 and 16 December 2019.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] During the 2022 Men's T20 World Cup, Perth Stadium hosted five out of the 45 matches that were played around the country in October 2022.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In October 2024, it was announced that Perth Stadium will host the first test of the 2025-2026 Men's Ashes; this was the first time Perth Stadium hosted an Ashes Test.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The most runs scored here in Test format is by Marnus Labuschagne (524 runs), followed by Travis Head (391 runs) and Steve Smith (371 runs).
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The most wickets taken here is by Nathan Lyon (29 wickets), Mitchell Starc (26 wickets) and Josh Hazlewood (16 wickets).
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The most runs scored here in ODI format is by Marcus Stoinis (109 runs), followed by Joe Root (62 runs) and Jason Roy (49 runs).
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The most wickets taken here is by Tom Curran (5 wickets) and Andrew Tye (5 wickets).
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium's cricket crowd record of 55,018 spectators was set during the 2025–26 Big Bash League Final between the Sydney Sixers and Perth Scorchers on 25 January 2026.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The National Rugby League played a double-header in round 1 of the 2018 NRL season in front of 38,842.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The second match of the 2019 State of Origin series between New South Wales and Queensland was played at Perth Stadium on 23 June 2019 and marked the first Origin game to be played in Western Australia.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] New South Wales defeated Queensland 38–6 in front of a crowd of 59,721.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 21 April 2021, it was announced that the second match of the 2022 State of Origin series was to be held at Perth Stadium after managing to secure the event from the Australian Rugby League Commission for an undisclosed sum.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] New South Wales defeated Queensland 44–12 in front of a crowd of 59,358.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 5 August 2023, the National Rugby League played a double-header in round 23 of the 2023 NRL season.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The first game was between the Dolphins (NRL) versus the Newcastle Knights which ended in Newcastle winning 28 - 30.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The second game was played between the South Sydney Rabbitohs and the Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks which resulted in Cronulla winning 16 - 26.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The overall attendance that day was a total of 45,814.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In August 2023, it was announced that Perth Stadium had secured the right to host State of Origin games in 2025 and 2028.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Queensland defeated New South Wales 26-24 in front of a crowd of 57,023 in the 2025 game.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium hosted the Australian leg of the 2019 Bledisloe Cup series, which doubled as a Rugby Championship match, in which the Wallabies beat New Zealand 47-26 on 10 August 2019 in front of 61,241.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The match was the first Bledisloe Cup Test to be held in Western Australia (the Subiaco Oval had previously hosted Mandela Challenge Plate tests in the Tri-Nations against South Africa) and set the stadium's highest single-day attendance record.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 30 January 2020, the Western Australian state government announced that the Springboks would play the Wallabies at the stadium as part of the 2020 Rugby Championship on 29 August 2020.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] This was, however, cancelled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] However, in 2024, it was announced that the Springboks would take on the Wallabies at the stadium on 17 August that year, marking the former team's first return to Perth since 2017.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Following the success of the match in 2019, it was announced that the Australian leg of the Bledisloe Cup would return to the stadium in 2021.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In September 2021 52,724 watched All Blacks beat the Wallabies 21–38.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In July 2022, the Wallabies hosted historic rivals England in a three-test series; the first match was played at Perth Stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Australia beat England 30–28 in front of 47,668.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In August 2024 the Springboks beat Australia 12–30 in their Rugby Championship matchup in front of 58,197.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In June 2025 the stadium hosted a crowd of 46,656 for British and Irish Lions 56–7 tour match victory over the Western Force.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium hosted a friendly match between Perth Glory and Chelsea on 23 July 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The 2019 A-League Grand Final was played at the stadium on 19 May 2019, which was the first time Perth Glory has hosted the grand final in the League's history.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The Grand Final broke the attendance record for an A-League finals series match, with 56,371 spectators.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Manchester United played two pre-season games at the stadium, one against Perth Glory on 13 July 2019 and the other against historic rival Leeds United on 17 July 2019.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In July 2022, English Premier League clubs Manchester United, Aston Villa, Leeds United, and Crystal Palace travelled to Perth to compete in ICON - Perth's Festival of International Football.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Crystal Palace played Leeds United on 22 July, and Manchester United played Aston Villa on 23 July.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 18 July 2023, Premier League clubs Tottenham Hotspur and West Ham United played a friendly pre-season game at Perth Stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Earlier, the latter club had played Perth Glory on 15 July.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 29 October 2023, Perth Stadium hosted a 2024 AFC Women's Olympic Qualifying Tournament match between the Matildas and the Philippines.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The crowd of 59,155 was the largest attendance for a soccer match (men or women) at the stadium, and was the largest home crowd recorded for an Australian women's sports event outside of an Olympic Games or a World Cup.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium also hosted a qualifying match between Chinese Taipei and Iran on the same date.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 31 May 2024, Italian clubs AC Milan and AS Roma played a friendly game at the stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The friendly was the two clubs' only game played in the Asia-Pacific region in 2024 and marked the return to Australia of AC Milan for the first time in 30 years and was AS Roma's first time in Perth since 1966.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 5 June 2025, the stadium hosted a 2026 FIFA World Cup qualifier against Japan, which was the Socceroos' penultimate game in this qualifying round, and crucial in securing direct qualification to the tournament.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Australia won the game 1–0 thanks to a 90th minute winner from Aziz Behich.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] This left the Socceroos only needing to avoid defeat by fewer than 5 goals against Saudi Arabia to qualify directly to the World Cup, on the final match day.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] If it had proceeded, it would have been the first major European league regular season game to be played overseas.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 1 March 2026, the 2026 AFC Women's Asian Cup opening ceremony and first group stage match between The Matildas and Philippines was held at the stadium, drawing 44,379 spectators.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The stadium also hosted a semi-final match between The Matildas and China PR on 17 March 2026, drawing 35,170 spectators.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Perth Stadium is also capable of hosting major concerts and other entertainment events.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Both Ed Sheeran and Taylor Swift performed at the venue in 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Nitro Circus performed at the stadium on 22 April 2018.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Eminem performed at the stadium on 27 February 2019.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] U2 performed at the Stadium on 27 November 2019 as part of their 2019 Joshua Tree tour.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] Queen + Adam Lambert performed at the Stadium on 23 February 2020 as part of their Rhapsody Tour.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 18 November 2022, Guns N' Roses performed at the stadium as part of their 2022 tour.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 12 February 2023, the Red Hot Chili Peppers and Post Malone performed at the stadium as part of the former act's Global Stadium Tour.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] In the current biggest ticketed single-event at the stadium, Ed Sheeran performed again on 12 March 2023 as part of his +–=÷x Tour.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] The YouTube channel How Ridiculous uploaded a video on 8 March 2023 that had been filmed at the stadium.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 18 and 19 November 2023, as part of their Music of the Spheres World Tour, Coldplay performed their only 2023 Australian shows at the stadium; it was the band's first shows in Perth since their Viva la Vida Tour in February 2009.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 1 and 2 March 2024, Pink performed at the stadium as part of her Summer Carnival tour.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] On 21 September 2023, WWE announced that the 2024 Elimination Chamber would be held at Perth Stadium on 24 February 2024.
[src:perth-stadium/perth-stadium] 52,590 spectators attended the event, which was the first WWE event held in Australia since 2018, and the only WWE event to be held in the Asia–Pacific region in 2024.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] The **+−=÷× Tour** (pronounced **The Mathematics Tour**) was the fourth concert tour by the English singer-songwriter Ed Sheeran.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] It began in Dublin, Ireland, on 23 April 2022, and concluded in Düsseldorf, Germany, on 7 September 2025.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] The +−=÷× Tour was designed as a tribute to Sheeran's math symbol studio albums.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] Spanning 188 shows across five continents, it became the fourth highest-grossing tour of all time with $875.7 million in ticket sales and the fourth highest-attended tour of all time with 8.8 million tickets sold.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] Sheeran's shows at the Melbourne Cricket Ground broke the record for the highest ticketed attendance at an Australian concert with 108,000 on 2 March 2023 and 110,000 the next day.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] His five Wembley Stadium concerts in 2022 became one of the most-attended multi-night engagement shows with over 420,000 tickets sold.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] Sheeran also broke the SoFi Stadium's one-day ticket record, performing to over 81,000 fans.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] Dating back to his first reported concert in 2012, Sheeran grossed over $1.7 billion from 18.9 million tickets sold and became one of the 10 highest grossing and bestselling acts in boxscore history.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] On 17 September 2021, Sheeran announced a 27-date European tour.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] As soon as tickets went on-sale, dates were added to several locations across the tour, due to overwhelming demand, bringing the overall number of shows to 64.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] On 15 March 2022, Sheeran announced the Oceania leg of the tour.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] On 22 March 2022, Sheeran added three more cities to the Oceania leg of the tour—in Brisbane, Sydney, and Melbourne.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] On 15 June 2022, Sheeran added a further three stops to the Oceania leg, in Wellington, Auckland, and Brisbane.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] On 20 September 2022, the additional Wellington show scheduled for 1 February 2023 was canceled, citing on-going uncertainties affecting a number of different variables with global touring.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] In October 2022, Sheeran announced that the North American leg of the tour would begin in 2023.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] In October 2023, he announced the Asian leg of the tour that would start in early 2024.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] In July 2024, he announced that the tour would end in 2025.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] In December 2024, Sheeran announced a show in Bhutan for early 2025, marking the country's first international concert.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] Sheeran brought his family (wife Cherry, and daughters Lyra and Jupiter) along on tour (though they do not appear with him onstage).
[src:perth-stadium/tour] During early 2023, they all lived together for two months in a rented bungalow in Auckland from which he commuted to the Australian and New Zealand venues.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] The "+−=÷× Tour" logo was first revealed on 6 May 2021 when Sheeran was announced as the shirt sponsor of Ipswich Town F.C. for their upcoming season in 2021–22 EFL League One, four months before the tour itself was announced.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] Sheeran's sponsorship deal with Ipswich Town lasted until the end of the 2024-25 season.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] This set list is representative of the show in Arlington, Texas on 6 May 2023.
[src:perth-stadium/tour] It does not represent all concerts for the duration of the tour.
